The car wasn't running and the heat was soaring, hitting a maximum of 96 degrees. Also locked inside: Dees' cell phone and purse.

'I was just sitting there, watching him get hotter and turn redder — and he was soaked with sweat, Dees told WFTS.

She begged a stranger to let her call 911 with his cell phone.

'My infant son is locked in the car in the parking lot,' Dees told the dispatcher, WFTS reported.

'It is so hot outside. I'm really concerned, like I don't think I have time to call AAA before he would suffer heat exhaustion. Can somebody come out and open the door? I don't even know if that is something you guys do.'

The dispatcher responded: 'They won't be able to try to gain access [to the] car unless the child is in some kind of distress and, well, by that point they may just smash your windows.'

The call went silent.

Some eight minutes later, an off-duty officer saw Dees' desperation and called 911 himself.

'Where are they at?' the second dispatcher said. 'We will be out there for her.'

Before the officers arrived, another CVS customer grabbed a wrench inside the store and broke one of the car's windows — rescuing baby Jack and handing him over to his mother.

